<DOC><DOCNO> AP900209-0078 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-09-90 0726EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-BRF--GangEnforcers     02-09 0155</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Gang Enforcers,0158</SECOND><HEAD>California Gang Reportedly Recruited in N.Y. Drug Wars</HEAD><DATELINE>CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Increased violence by drug dealerstrying to establish turf in western New York has prompted somedealers to enlist members of a notorious California gang to fighttheir battles, police said.   Police, who have suspected that members of the Los Angeles-basedCrips were in Buffalo for the past 18 months, on Wednesday arrestedsix people believed to be Crips.   ``Our investigation indicates they were being brought in toassist in retaliations of narcotics shootings in Buffalo,'' saidLt. M. James Starr, in charge of the Cheektowaga police narcoticsdivision.   Buffalo police estimate about 20 Crips now live in Buffalo.   The Crips are major traffickers of crack cocaine, according to astudy by the Drug Enforcement Administration in 1989. Along withthe ``Bloods'' and Jamaican posses, they are described as``extremely violent'' and ``operate on a `no innocent bystander'theory.''</TEXT></DOC>